How you can make your iPhone videos feel more cinematic:

* Lighting is everything. If your light is poor, your video will be poor. Shoot in soft light or golden hour. 
* Use the ×2 or ×3 lens for compression 
* If your iPhone model has cinematic mode, try it out. 
* Shoot 60fps and slow your clips down to make them feel smoother. 
* Underexposed your videos slightly when filming
* Use slow smooth camera movements
* Don’t zoom.

Five fun facts you might not know about about highland cows: 

1. Highland cows, also known as Highland cattle or "coos" in Scotland, are a Scottish breed of cattle known for their distinctive long horns and shaggy coats. They are one of the oldest registered breeds of cattle in the world, with a history dating back over 400 years.

2. Highland cows are adapted to harsh environments and are well-suited for rugged terrain and cold climates. Their long, thick double coat provides insulation and protection against the elements, allowing them to graze and thrive in areas where other cattle breeds may struggle. 

3. Despite their shaggy appearance, Highland cows have a gentle and docile temperament. They are known for their calm and friendly nature. However, they are also known to be very protective of their calves. (Jolene’s going to be fun.)

4. The horns of Highland cows are iconic. Both males (bulls) and females (cows) have horns. The horns of bulls tend to have a more pronounced forward curve or sweep, often forming a semi-circular shape. The horns of cows are usually more upright and have a slight curve. 

5. Around the globe, full sized highlands are primarily raised for their meat, which is highly regarded for its flavor and tenderness. The meat is lean and has low levels of cholesterol and fat compared to other beef breeds. Their milk is also used to produce a variety of dairy products, although they are not as commonly used for milk production as dairy-specific breeds.

One of the most impressive features on an iPhone is the Cinematic Mode for video. 

Cinematic Mode is all about the “bokeh” effect, which creates a beautiful, soft background blur while keeping the main subject sharp and in focus, drawing the viewer’s attention to the central element of the scene.

Cinematic Mode anticipates focus shifts, making it great for capturing dynamic scenes. It recognizes when the subject moves towards or away from the camera, ensuring that the focus transitions remain smooth and natural throughout the video.

But sometimes I want to take creative control and select the area of focus myself. 

It’s as easy as tapping the screen while you’re recording but you can also change the focus points after you record the video too. 

Watch as I I’ll walk you through how to change the focus points after you’ve taken the video, using he photos app on your phone. 

It takes just a minute or two and can really make a difference in the final video. 

Share with your friends if you found this video helpful. ♥️

Companies and news outlets invested in plant-based alternatives and lab-grown meat continue to exaggerate the impact of animal agriculture in efforts to convert meat-eaters to their products, mostly in the name of environmental health. 

But in reality, if Americans choose to forgo meat, it would have a minimal and short-term impact on the climate.

Given the fact that we’ve seen strong decreases in U.S. cattle herds over the past 50 years (without a corresponding decrease in output), they’ve been helping to mitigate climate change for years. 

Plus, American farmers and ranchers continue to make advances in efficiencies, and progress on methane-reducing digesters and feed additives is ongoing and promising. 

Not only is animal agriculture not our biggest problem, but with decreasing methane scenarios, it may well be a significant part of the solution.

iPhone Live photos are the best! Think of it as taking a photo + video at the same time. When Live mode is turned on, the camera captures 1.5 seconds of video before and after you press the shutter button.

It’s a perfect option if you have a subject that is always moving.

…And it’s easy! 

Step 1: Open the photos app on your phone and find the live image you want to edit. Click ‘edit’ in the upper right-hand corner of the screen.

Step 2: Click the “LIVE” icon. (It’s at the bottom and looks like a bullseye.) 🎯 

Step 3: Use the slider to choose the frame that is the best pose and select ‘Make Key Photo’ and hit done.

That’s it! Use it on any subject that’s moving like kids, cows or Heath…cause he’s a mover and a blinker in every pic! 😉 

It’s true. Never worry about blinks again. If this tip was helpful let me know in the comments. ♥️

It’s that time of the week again when we head out to make sure our cattle are healthy and happy. 

🐄 **Herd Health Check**: We start by walking through the cattle while we feed them pellets and check herd health. Pellets do have some nutritional value but we use them mostly to tame the herd. Some ranchers call them cake, or cubes or cow crack 😆. Cattle go crazy for them. 

📋 **Cattle Count**: Counting our cattle helps us keep track of their numbers. It’s also a chance to make sure everyone is present and accounted for. A good headcount ensures that no one is missing or in need of special attention.

💧 **Water, Minerals, and Salt Blocks**: We check the water tanks to be sure they’re full and working properly. We also refill the mineral and salt blocks to make sure they have access to the nutrients they need.

🏞️ **Pasture Patrol**: We drive the fences around the pasture, looking for a fallen branch, a loose fence, or anything out of the ordinary. Cattle are amazing at finding a missing fence staple or low wire or basically anything at all to get on the other side of a fence. 

🌿 **Grass and Forage Quality**: We pay attention to the quality of the pasture grass. Is there still enough grass? If not, we rotate the herd to another area. 

🌅 **Bonding Time**: Beyond the practical aspects, these weekly checks are also a chance for us to spend a little extra time with each other and with our cattle. It’s a shared responsibility that deepens our connection to the land and the animals and each other. 

So, here’s to another week of caring for our cattle. It’s not always glamorous, but it’s a labor of love, and we wouldn’t have it any other way. 

Thanks for following along! 
♥️ Heath + Sara

How you can make your iPhone videos feel more cinematic:

* Lighting is everything. If your light is poor, your video will be poor. Try to shoot in soft light or golden hour when the sun is low. 
* Use the ×2 or ×3 lens for compression 
* If your iPhone model has cinematic mode, try it out. 
* Slow your clips down. 
* Underexposed your videos slightly when filming
* Use slooooooow smooth camera movements
* Don’t pinch zoom.

A little character building…I mean fence building has been keeping us busy around here. The weather has been warmer than normal so we’re taking full advantage!

And here’s to more of it in 2024. For me it means more art, more creativity, documenting more scenes that move me…and in turn, might move you. 

I’m excited to bring you more big camera pictures and video this year after my creativity tanked to an all time low this past year. 

Last January I bought a new camera and honestly struggled all year to pick it up. I tried to love it without reallllllly sitting down and learning it. Nothing ever felt right. I tried shooting for other people thinking that added pressure would magically make me better. 

It didn’t. And any pictures I did take are dying a slow death on my hard drive. (sorry Jordan)

Turns out, like everything in life, there’s no real shortcut. You have to put in the time and be willing to suck at something new for a while. 

This last month, I stepped back some from socials to clear my head and decided to take the advice I’ve been giving others for years. 👇🏻

Get out there and take pictures everyday. You’ll feel yourself getting better with each click. Try new things and fail. Repeat, repeat, repeat until you can focus on your creativity and not the buttons. 

I feel my creativity coming back again and I’m excited about it. I’ve even been digging into video on the big camera which is a BEAST and something I’ve been struggling with for years. 

If you made it this far, thanks for sticking around. I hope you let yourself be a beginner at something new this year!
